DATA CLEANING

◈ In the above stats we can see that there are people with 0 BP (dead person?), 0 skin thickness (skeleton?) and 0 Glucose (how do you even survive?).With the following code we are going to replace instances with null value in the selected columns with more appropriate values.
◈ To be precise I am going to use random values around the mean of the column as substitutes. The range will be from the mean - 1.2 the standard deviation, to the mean + 1.2 the standard deviation.
◈ This will allow us to avoid an equal value for each datum, but we are not going to skew the distribution of the dataset.


In [5]:
#data cleaning process 
for col in ["Glucose", "BloodPressure", "SkinThickness", "Insulin", "BMI"]:
    mean = data[data[col] != 0][col].mean()
    std = data[data[col] != 0][col].std()

    values = data[col].values

    np.random.seed(23)

    for i, val in enumerate(values):
        if val == 0:
            values[i] = mean + std * (np.random.rand() * 2 - 1) * 1.2
    data[col] = pd.Series(values).astype(data[col].dtype)

◈ Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) is an approach to analyze the data using visual techniques. It is used to discover trends, patterns, or to check assumptions with the help of statistical summary and graphical representations.

◈ The hist() function is used to create histograms.This method bins the data x and count.Here for each of the attributes in the dataset "data", a histogram is created.

◈ A pointplot is a type of plot used to visualize the relationship between two variables, one of which is categorical and the other is numeric. It is similar to a lineplot, but instead of drawing a line to connect the points, it draws a point at the mean or median value of each category and extends a line representing a confidence interval around the point.

◈ kdeplot and histplot are two types of plots used to visualize the distribution of a numeric variable. Although both plots are similar in nature, they have some key differences in terms of their purpose and the information they convey.
◈ Kdeplot, short for Kernel Density Estimate plot, is to provide a smooth estimate of the underlying distribution of the data, without binning the data into discrete categories. Histplot, short for Histogram plot,is to provide a visual representation of the distribution of the data, including the central tendency, variability, and shape.

CORRELATION REPRESENTED USING HEATMAPS

◈ Variables within a dataset can be related for lots of reasons. It can be useful in data analysis and modeling to better understand the relationships between variables. The statistical relationship between two variables is referred to as their correlation. ◈ A correlation could be positive, meaning both variables move in the same direction, or negative, meaning that when one variable’s value increases, the other variables’ values decrease. Correlation can also be neural or zero, meaning that the variables are unrelated.

LOGISTIC REGRESSION

◈ Logistic regression aims to solve classification problems. It does this by predicting categorical outcomes, unlike linear regression that predicts a continuous outcome.
◈ In the simplest case there are two outcomes, which is called binomial, an example of which is predicting if a tumor is malignant or benign. Other cases have more than two outcomes to classify, in this case it is called multinomial.

In our dataset, the main objective is to study whether a person has Diabetes or not.Therefore outcomes are either 0 or 1 and hence Logistic Regression model can be used.


In [133]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
log_reg = LogisticRegression(C=1,penalty='l2')
log_reg.fit(X_train,Y_train)

log_acc=accuracy_score(Y_test,log_reg.predict(X_test))


print("Train Set Accuracy:"+str(accuracy_score(Y_train,log_reg.predict(X_train))*100))
print("Test Set Accuracy:"+str(accuracy_score(Y_test,log_reg.predict(X_test))*100))

RANDOM FOREST CLASSIFIER

◈ Random Forest is a popular machine learning algorithm that belongs to the supervised learning technique. It can be used for both Classification and Regression problems in ML. It is based on the concept of ensemble learning, which is a process of combining multiple classifiers to solve a complex problem and to improve the performance of the model.

◈ As the name suggests, "Random Forest is a classifier that contains a number of decision trees on various subsets of the given dataset and takes the average to improve the predictive accuracy of that dataset." Instead of relying on one decision tree, the random forest takes the prediction from each tree and based on the majority votes of predictions, and it predicts the final output.


In [88]:

rfc_acc = accuracy_score(Y_test,rfc.predict(X_test))

DECISION TREE CLASSIFIER

◈Decision Tree is a Supervised learning technique that can be used for both classification and Regression problems, but mostly it is preferred for solving Classification problems. It is a tree-structured classifier, where internal nodes represent the features of a dataset, branches represent the decision rules and each leaf node represents the outcome.It is a graphical representation for getting all the possible solutions to a problem/decision based on given conditions.

◈ There are various algorithms in Machine learning, so choosing the best algorithm for the given dataset and problem is the main point to remember while creating a machine learning model. Below are the two reasons for using the Decision tree:
▸ Decision Trees usually mimic human thinking ability while making a decision, so it is easy to understand.
▸ The logic behind the decision tree can be easily understood because it shows a tree-like structure.


In [135]:

CONCLUSION

Though Diabetes can be rooted to various factors, the main factor that plays a significant role is Glucose ( infer the correlation matrix heatmap ).In turn the Glucose levels are highly correlated with Insulin.Insulin levels of a person is influenced by overeating, inactivity and genetics.

The test accuracy level of the models are low compared to the Train set accuracy level.Some of the reasing causing this include:

  • Insufficient data: One of the most common causes of low accuracy is having insufficient data to train the model. This can happen if the dataset is too small. In this case, the model may not have enough information to learn from which can lead to low accuracy.
  • Lack of feature engineering:Feature engineering is the process of selecting and designing features for a machine learning model. If the features used to train the model are not well designed or relevant, the model may have difficulty learning from the data and may have low accuracy.
